CSA stands in solidarity with the #BlackLivesMatter movement.CSA was founded on the principles of non-racialism & inclusion at unity.The vision of CSA, to become a truly national sport of winners supported by the majority, finds resonance in the ethos of “Black Lives Matter”. https://t.co/Wsf65ckY3Y
Our cricket development programmes have proven demonstrably that we strive to work towards the constitutional promise of a redress and equality for all.
"Black Lives Matter. It is as simple as that." - CSA Acting CEO Dr Jacques Faul said.

"As a national sporting body representing more than 56 million South Africans & with the privileged position of owning a platform as large as we do, it is of vital importance that we use our voice to educate and listen to others on topics involving all forms of discrimination."
“During our celebrations of Nelson Mandela International Day on 18 July, CSA will further spread the message of anti-racism through the #BlackLivesMatter campaign." - Dr Jacques Faul

"We will also speak out against all forms of violence and in particular, the scourge that is Gender Based Violence and various other causes that are of importance to our society and the organization.” - Dr Jacques Faul, Acting CEO of CSA

Aligned with the commemoration of the Day of the African Child and under #DAC2020 theme “Access to a Child Friendly Justice System in Africa”, @_AfricanUnion and @UNICEF, have launched the #NoNameCampaign: For every child legal identity, for every child access to justice”. https://t.co/eeSU27BR4F

Registration at birth, is one of the key elements to accelerate access to a child-friendly justice system for all children. The #NoNameCampaign seeks to rally for the speedy implementation of commitments by AU member states, towards universal registration of children at birth.

The #NoNameCampaign recognizes the urgency to reposition civil registration and vital statistics in Africa, to address the indignity of invisibility. The campaign is equally timely as concerns rise on the threat of birth registration rates falling behind amid #COVID19 pandemic

#NoNameCampaign underlines that children whose births are not registered & who lack proof of their age are more vulnerable to marginalization, discrimination, abuse & associated protection risks such as child marriage, child labour, forced recruitment to armed groups &trafficking https://t.co/T5ApDdzpDD

On #AfricanPublicServiceDay download the African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration from https://t.co/qa3BjMEHqH  & learn about the principles for Africa’s public service sector & find out if your country has ratified the treaty. https://t.co/exAWFff18R

Public Service and Administration and its agents shall respect the human rights, dignity and integrity of all users. Article 4 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration  #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Public Service shall be organised to ensure easy access to adequate services and shall be organised to ensure that services are delivered closer to users. Article 5  African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Public Service and Administration shall make available to users information on procedures and formalities pertaining to public service delivery. Article 6 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Public services shall be delivered in the most effective, efficient and economical manner, consistent with the highest possible standards. Article 7 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay https://t.co/JGtXhZhaCc

Public Service and Administration shall facilitate the introduction of modern and innovative procedures and systems for the delivery of its services. Article 8 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Public  Service  Agents  shall  demonstrate professionalism,  transparency and impartiality in the performance oftheir duties. Article 9 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Public Service Agents shall be required to perform their professional duties and show courtesy, integrity and neutrality in dealing with users. Article 9 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Public Service Agents shall demonstrate integrity and respect all rules, values and established codes of conduct in the performance of  their duties. Article 10 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Public Service Agents shall not solicit, accept, or receive directly or indirectly any payment, gift, donation, or reward in kind or cash, for services rendered. Article 10 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Public Service Agents shall on no account use their positions for political or personal gains. In all circumstances, they shall act with impartiality and loyalty. Article 10 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

States shall enact laws and adopt strategies to fight corruption through the establishment of independent anti-corruption institutions. Article 12 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Public Service Agents shall declare their assets & income at the beginning, during and at the end of their service as prescribed in national laws & regulations. Article 13 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Article 11 “Public Service Agents shall not occupy any position, engage in transactions, hold financial,commercial, material interest incompatible with their duties or responsibilities” #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Article 14 “Public Service and Administration shall not encourage or perpetuate discrimination based on origin, race, gender, disability, religion, ethnicity, political opinion or any other consideration.” #AfricanPublicServiceDay

Article 17 Public Service Agents shall have the right, within a coherent and harmonized pay system, to a just and equitable remuneration which corresponds to their qualifications, responsibilities, performance and tenure.#AfricanPublicServiceDay

Public Service and Administration shall protect its agents against all forms of threats, insults, harassment oraggression. Article 16 African Charter on Values & Principles of Public Service & Administration #AfricanPublicServiceDay

In partnership with @UNDPSouthAfrica we're hosting a conference for African election management bodies on the impact of social media on the integrity of elections at the Cape Town International Convention Centre from 2–5 March. #SocialMediaandElections https://t.co/Ntd2EN8DLI

IEC South Africa Vice-chairperson Janet Love on the rationale for the conference on social media and elections, 2-5 March 2020, Cape Town. Social media's impact on elections https://t.co/rD3CUYNxyD via @YouTube

More than 170 delegates from over 34 election management bodies across Africa are arriving in Cape Town today, Monday 2 March, for a four-day conference exploring the risks and rewards social media poses to elections. #SocialMediaandElections

Conference ‘Safeguarding Electoral Integrity in the Digital Age: Strategies for Combatting Digital Disinformation’ will bring together experts from Africa & beyond to share experiences in maximising benefits & mitigating risks of social media for electoral integrity in Africa.

“Growth & increasing popularity of social media has brought with it great benefits to electoral democracy including rapid, convenient & cost-effective distribution of information to the electorate by political parties, candidates & election management bodies” -IEC CEO Sy Mamabolo

“Social media has become an integral part of almost all aspects of elections in most modern democracies – including in voter registration, political campaigning & sharing of information regarding the election process, outcomes and results." -Sy Mamabolo, CEO of IEC South Africa

As defenders electoral democracy, election management bodies must continually seek ways of enhancing and protecting the integrity of the election process – incl understanding how to reap the rewards & mitigate risks posed by advances in digital technology.” -Sy Mamabolo, IEC CEO

"By raising awareness & stimulating debate & discussion among EMBs, social media platforms, political parties & other stakeholders, we are laying the foundation for preventing the abuse of social media & combatting digital misinformation." -Dr Ayodele Odusola of @UNDPSouthAfrica

The #SocialMediaandElections conference begins tonight, 2 March, with a keynote address by the Minister of 
@HomeAffairsSA Dr Aaron Motsoaledi followed by 3 days of engagements and interactions between the delegates. More info at https://t.co/sCZ9pr0qQs. @UNDPSouthAfrica
@ZweSibiya Please follow us here and on our Facebook page where we will be live-streaming and tweeting from the conference. Thanks for your interest.

IEC chairperson Glen Mashinini welcomes representatives from over 34 African election management bodies to the #SocialMediaandElections conference opening. "We are humbled by the overwhelming response, that is testimony to the importance of this event."

"How can social media contribute to democratisation in Africa in general and electoral integrity in particular? That is the question we need to answer," says @_AfricanUnion's Dr Khabele Matlosa in his welcome message at the #SocialMediaandElections conference. https://t.co/7v6q9M0v7U
"This event will shift the frontiers of election management in Africa," says Dr Ayodele Odusola, Resident Representative of @UNDPSouthAfrica at the opening of the #SocialMediaandElections conference.

"We need a solution that balances human rights & right to freedom of speech & political rights & right to vote. The Electoral Commission notes the judgment of the Constitutional Court declaring the Electoral Act unconstitutional in so far as it requires candidates to contest national and provincial elections only as a member of a political party. Full statement at https://t.co/7VSTtytIGg

“We welcome the clarity the Court has given to interpretation of rights of citizens to stand for public office. We will study the judgment to reflect on full implications for electoral system & legislative framework governing national & prov elections”-Chairperson Glen Mashinini

The timing of this judgment, and the Parliamentary review of the electoral system it prompts, is opportune given both the maturing of South Africa’s democracy and the looming impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on election processes around the world.

The Court has provided Parliament with 24 months to revise the legislation and the Electoral Commission stands ready to provide technical assistance into this process to help enhance our electoral system.

Good Morning Entrepreneurs today is Monday and we hope all of you are back to the grind and making things to happen. This will be a thread message on Enterprise Development and how you can start, develop and sustain your enterprise and an #entrepreneur in South Africa

Businesses serve a critical role in driving more inclusive and sustainable development. Large companies can create positive impact by improving and growing development. Corporates can achieve this by including small business into their value chains and local communities.

Helping small businesses achieve sustainability and growth is vital for both the development of industries and corporations. Small businesses are critical for job creation, improving living standards, raising #productivity and achieving inclusive #economic growth.

In the coming years there will be a great demand for jobs and the private sector will be the core to the solution of this challenge. Many of the jobs will come out of the small, medium and micro-enterprises, which is why enterprise development programmes are emerging globally.

Maybe you might be asking yourself the BIG question of "What is an enterprise development programme?". Enterprise development involves the growing of black #SMMEs through the provision of finance and support, assisting in their business development and sustainability.

In creating a programme for enterprise development, budding entrepreneurs and all they hire will earn a living, which in turn uplifts their quality of life. These programmes could lead to long term economic growth for entrepreneurs, their families and their entire communities.

The enterprise development programme is just one of the elements of BB-BEE and is considered an effective way to combat poverty across the globe. Its objective is to teach potential entrepreneurs how to create a sustainable business that will grow and increase job creation.
nterprise development programmes ought to be aimed at transferring skills and wealth as well as leading to the sustainable growth of small businesses.
Let's look at you as an entrepreneur that owns an #SMME enterprise or business can benefit from enterprise development.

Enterprise development programmes aim to pass on knowledge, experience and business support. This aim will provide start-ups with essential tools and resources that can then be used for the development, survival and success of business.

Enterprise development programmes aim to pass on knowledge, experience and business support. This aim will provide start-ups with essential tools and resources that can then be used for the development, survival and success of business.

Essential tools and resources can be divided into financial and non-financial support. Non-financial support can be provided in the form of mentorship, market access, network access and the learning of new skills.

80% of South Africa’s start-ups fail in the first three years and this is largely attributed to a lack of support. However, the survival rate of a start-up is increased by the incubation process, which assists small businesses in becoming financially viable.

The Gordon Institute of Business Science (GIBS) and FNB’s Entrepreneurial Dialogues, State of Entrepreneurship in South Africa report revealed that: “Business incubators assist emerging companies survive and grow during the start-up period, when they are most vulnerable...

...The incubation process improves the survival rate of start-up companies by assisting them to become financially viable, usually within two to three years.” The FNB/GIBSs report explains: “Start-ups fail at a rate of about nine in ten in the first two years of operation...

..within the 27 SEDA incubators (in operation), the survival rates are in the region of 84% to 97% in the first two years of operation. Post-graduation from the incubator, the numbers come down but they are still in excess of 70%.”

Why do corporate businesses offer enterprise development? The B-BBEE Amendments are providing corporate South Africa with an ideal opportunity to construct sustainable businesses and to play a lead role in the socioeconomic transformation of the country.

Investment and improvement in local economies can ensure profitability and economic success for all business around the world. By offering an enterprise development programme corporates are awarded:

1. Points on the BEE scorecard
2. An opportunity to diversify their supply chain

3. An innovative way to increase business for both small and medium sized enterprises.

It’s an inspiring vision for business to play a real role in the sustainability and growth in the country’s economy

THREAD: Today we unravel the conspiracy in the Mediterranean where the EU and Italy flouted international law in a deadly bid to stop migrants reaching Europe
The evidence shows European air assets acting as the eyes & ears of the Libyan coastguard. Providing an interception force to return migrants to Libya in violation of international law
It's there in audio recordings, unpublished letters between high-level EU mandarins, confirmed by inside sources & laid bare in emails from the Libyan coastguard

Mercedes-Benz South Africa is aware of a recent social media post alleging that the company is not adhering to the required safety precautions at our Pretoria head office as well as a positive case of COVID-19.
We wish to state categorically that these claims are false and the safety of our employees and customers remains our primary concern.

Based on an important need to continue servicing and maintaining the vehicles of essential service providers, as well as operate an effective roadside assistance service for our customers, we have begun a very controlled return to operations.

This return to operations is in accordance with the Occupational Health and Safety Act of 1993 in governing workplaces in relation to COVID–19, the prescriptions of the government’s Alert Level 4 restrictions, and in adherence to strict health and safety protocols.

These protocols include the use of safe communication methods, the use of personal protective equipment, the practise of social distancing, on-site safety reminders, online service bookings and the deep cleaning of our facilities.

We would like to assure our employees, contractors and other key stakeholders that we have gone to every length to ensure their safety during this time.

Stay safe.

The Mercedes-Benz South Africa Team

I get lots of requests for advice or mentorship. Often, the person requesting hasn’t done basics: 

1. Research your field! Know everything you need about your industry first! 

2. Research me! Read my blog posts, watch my talks. That’s the best way to get advice from me. 1/

3. Be specific. Ask a very precise question that Google didn’t answer. 

4. Be concise. I don’t have time to review a 30 page business plan. 

5. Start by trying to execute and ask if you run into challenges. Don’t waste my time with ‘I have this idea.’ 2/

You say you need just ten minutes of my time, but 10 X number of requests I get daily adds up and takes time from my business where I earn money. 

And it never takes 10 minutes!

If you can’t express your project and your needs concisely, it’s not mature enough to ask for help.

Check first for local support. So many contact me when they haven’t even tried with their local tech hub. These hubs are equipped to provide support for entrepreneurs and most programs are free. For a list of African hubs look here: https://t.co/geUXMJjqyP

The #ONEAfricaAward celebrates innovative African initiatives to fight extreme poverty and achieve the SDGs. The winner will be awarded $100k to ensure they can continue their work.

The African Institute For Development Policy – @Afidep – is a regional nonprofit research policy institute. It seeks to address gaps between research, policy, and practice in development efforts in Africa. #ONEAfricaAward https://t.co/G2YmKKyRic
The Msichana Initiative – @MsichanaUwezo – is based in Tanzania and advocates for girl’s empowerment, and policy and legal reforms. #ONEAfricaAward https://t.co/s1zi9SAceU

Working in Ghana, Agrisolve – @AgrisolveGh – is passionate about changing the outlook of farming among women using investment, advocacy and support schemes, where women constitute about 45% of the agricultural labour force. #ONEAfricaAward https://t.co/B4cxAvd0vC

Finally, the Public and Private Development Centre (PPDC) – @ppmonitorNG – is a Nigerian NGO focusing on improvements to primary healthcare, primary education, and education governance. #ONEAfricaAward https://t.co/mAXXJD4Ltq

Around 65% of the Equalisers we spoke to said they had access to the internet at home, but around 25% of this group said they struggle with network connection problems. #ReopeningSchools

While the Minister, last night referred to the use of TV & radio to support learners who are not yet back in school, our conversations with Equalisers during lockdown revealed some challenges. #ReopeningSchools
Learners said they struggled to concentrate, the lessons moved at a rapid rate, the content was new & unfamiliar & the sessions were not interactive enough. #ReopeningSchools

Education inequalities prior to & beyond Covid-19

While the focus in the current moment has been on #Covid19 compliance, most learners will return to schools that face the same inequalities that existed before the pandemic. #ReopeningSchools

The edu depts should have addressed school infrastructure challenges by complying with the legally binding Norms & Standards for Public School Infrastructure, but have failed to do so. #ReopeningSchools

The recent tabling of the #supplementarybudget, which sought to address #Covid19 related expenditure, dealt a blow to the education sector. We are extremely concerned about the outlook for basic education now & in the long-term. #ReopeningSchools

Despite facing demonstrable funding shortfalls before the #Covid19 crisis, basic education has not been provided with new funds to cope with Covid-19. This is symptomatic of government’s commitment to austerity budgeting despite a massive socio-economic crisis. #ReopeningSchools

Recent cuts to education funding will have an impact on the right to basic education & equality for learners across the country. We will continue to agitate for our demands on school infrastructure, scholar transport & school safety to be met. #ReopeningSchools

Schools must not just be #Covid19 compliant, they must be environments that protect the dignity & safety of learners & school staff, & that are conducive to quality teaching & learning. #ReopeningSchools

From 1-30 June, we surveyed Gr 7 & 12 learners, asking them to report conditions in their school & how they felt about attending school. EE received 485 responses from 123 Equalisers in 133 schools. The survey was conducted in 5 provinces in which EE organises. #ReopeningSchools https://t.co/TfTPl2K4gS https://t.co/i1t8DRbv5V

Learners were asked: When thinking about how my school is managing my safety with regards to #COVID19, do you want to be at school or want to be at home?
79.6% of all respondents reported that they want to be at school, with 20.4% saying they want to be at home. #ReopeningSchools https://t.co/8uQP6jCrZd https://t.co/bXJ2rIaP6N

When categorising sentiment into negative, neutral & positive, a significant majority (229/59.3%) of the learners who want to be at school report feeling fine or scared about being at school. 157 of these learners report feeling either satisfied or happy. #ReopeningSchools https://t.co/9WGTukRFM9

97.7% of respondents reported all their classes consisted of less than 40 learners. However, three learners in the Eastern Cape & one learner in Gauteng reported that none of their classes had less than 40 learners. #ReopeningSchools https://t.co/goC23g8ahF https://t.co/EW8avpYFNn

Today marks the twenty fourth day since the #JoziToStellenbosch Comrades embarked on the revolutionary walk from Jozi to Stellenbosch.

We salute you #JoziToStellenbosch movement Comrades for taking on this tremendous and selfless act of sacrificing your safety and health in aid of this struggle.

Equal Education, at its third National Congress, resolved to demonstrate solidarity with the struggles of the Black working class. We vowed to be in solidarity with all struggles of inequities faced by Black people & the #JoziToStellenbosch movements speaks directly  to this.

We are in solidarity with you Comrades: we support the cause of true liberation. We are together Comrades; to protect ourselves against repression we take a trowel in our right hand & a shield & sword in our left, to contribute to the task of rebuilding Afrika #JoziToStellenbosch

We are here to say our nation & the whole continent of Afrika must be free & it shall be free. We recognise the full worth of this action to free SA & its people. We choose now, tomorrow may be too late. #JoziToStellenbosch

Our politics are clear on non-violent radicalism. We radically believe that it is time that we reimagine a new liberated South Africa & continent. #JoziToStellenbosch

This happens when national & provincial govt are not committed enough to comply with the Norms & Standards for Public School Infrastructure. Since 2017 EE members in this school have called for @DebbieSchafer @WCEDnews to replace *temporary* prefab structures. What’s the plan? https://t.co/oW4X5c6Cxr

Bardale Primary & Bardale Secondary, & Parliament Primary in Mfuleni, are among schools in WC made completely of prefab structures. Prefabs are not in accordance with spirit of Norms & Standards – to provide safe & dignified teaching & learning spaces to all public schools.

MEC @DebbieSchafer must announce her plan to replace temporary structures with proper classrooms. If there is not a plan, the WCED must develop one and share it with the public. She must be held to account for the persistence of inadequate school infrastructure in her province!

And that @TreasuryRSA recently took money away from school infrastructure budget (funds for permanent school buildings to meaningfully address education inequality) its clear that the national government *still* doesn’t recognise how serious a problem overcrowded classrooms are!

EE members have long spoken about the conditions of Nomzamo High School. Filmed in 2016 by EE Equalisers, "We Are Not Failures, We Are Being Failed!" documents the sanitation conditions of different schools in CT including - from 9 mins - Nomzamo. https://t.co/hJP3hucNK8

In 2017, EE's annual infrastructure statement expressly noted that Nomzamo only had prefab classrooms and noted their inadequacy. Nothing was done. Its nothing short of negligence by the state collectively. What if learners had been in those prefabs!

🔗: https://t.co/ROiJYYLnOr https://t.co/1hz6kVSRa9

Nomzamo also serves as one of the starkest visual examples of education inequality in South Africa. Across the N2 sits Reddam House Somerset, a private school. In the picture below you can see the two schools, with Nomzamo just in the frame in the centre-top right of the picture. https://t.co/axsy1Aq9M2

We say it without hesitation, ALL schools in SA can look like Reddam. The fact that they don't is a failure of political will & government performance. On the left is Reddam House Somerset, on the left the new Chief Henry Bokeleni SSS in Libode. We could do it if we wanted to. https://t.co/QHdOtZOmz5

Lets get organised on this and ensure Nomzamo learners aren't left in the lurch. Tweet @DebbieSchafer & @WCED_HOD and ask them for detailed plans for both immediate and long term solutions for Nomzamo. We must expect a decisive intervention from them. # NoMoreWaiting

Lets also write to Reddam House & ask them to show social solidarity in the face of a disaster occuring during a pandemic by temporarily making classroom space available for matric learners to continue their finals preparations close to their school. 

info.somerset@reddam.house

Equal Education KZN, Community Leader: Nkululeko Ndima

“I am Nkululeko Ndima, from KwaZulu Natal, and I am gay. So since I came out life hasn't been easy for me, because of my family and the community that surrounds me." #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay https://t.co/SiVFPpj1k9

"I live in a mini rural area & it scares me how people take my sexuality. It has been hard for me for the longest time having to face discrimination, homophobia, & exclusion but since I joined EE things have been different." - Nkululeko Ndima #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay

"My experience since I came out was tough because I got abused twice & it made me hate the world so bad, even the people in it. Being a survivor of abuse is not easy & it's not something that will pass overnight." - Nkululeko Ndima #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay

"It's a traumatic experience that a lot of queer people have to deal with because of the continuous violence against us. I've been hurting for the longest time & I still do because all I want is justice." - Nkululeko Ndima #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay

"Being victimised by a family member cuts so deep & there's nothing you can do about that when you don't have the support & care you need at that time. When you can't feel the love of your family you go through a lot." - Nkululeko Ndima #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay

"I don't want to force my family to accept me. I just want them to UNDERSTAND the life I'm living. Since I've joined EE life has changed because I've been talking to people & I've found a family that loves, understands & accepts me" - Nkululeko Ndima #PrideEveryMonth

"I've grown emotionally, physically, & mentally. It's now about me advocating for human rights in every way I know how. So, let them love what they want to love, accept, understand & live with & I'll stand with being gay every second of my life” - Nkululeko Ndima #PrideEveryMonth

Equaliser, GP : Kamohelo Mofokeng 

“For me, it’s a bit hard being openly gay because society treats us badly. They often have hateful words like moffies & stabane. These words demean us and can cause low self-esteem in one’s life." #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay https://t.co/pKhk0jokFs

EE, WC Facilitator: Andiswa Boya 

“Being queer & a womxn has always been separated. You could finally be a womxn but not queer too. Being & seeing both at the same time has always been a fight. If not with self then with the country & community." #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay https://t.co/9xdK9yhinI

"You have to constantly apologise for being both as if you are asking for too much acceptance or attention. I am not just any queer womxn in SA, I am a black queer womxn in SA therefore I am automatically at the bottom & seeking attention." - Andiswa Boya #PrideEveryMonth

"I can't be fully out & proud because I have to choose. My freedom comes with either choosing to be queer, womxn, or black in a day. I can't be all three or I'll suffocate to death. Well, I suffocate every day when I have to choose because I can't."- Andiswa Boya #PrideEveryMonth

"I AM A BLACK QUEER WOMXN & that is who I am every day & that's who SA cannot accept. To be in a movement like EE means being "all three" at the same time, black queer womxn but having to fight and try to breathe within the space." - Andiswa Boya #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay

"It means apologising for being "too emotional/too womxn", it means being liberated & celebrated as a black person but I'm not really sure what that means for womxn, for me yet." - Andiswa Boya #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay

"I am still trying to find my feet, my space at EE but also I pray the space becomes more transparent & real as it is on policies & on its membership constitution. I pray it becomes more intellectual & more accepting." - Andiswa Boya #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay

"I pray we become more open about real stuff that affects the marginalised within the space & always be willing to engage & share our thoughts truthfully in a safe space." - Andiswa Boya #PrideEveryMonth #PrideEveryDay

"I pray we as EE become an open & safe space as we see ourselves. I really pray we learn & unlearn. I have breathed within that space. I truly pray we really turn to be as inclusive as we wish & when we do we are ready to take it all.” - Andiswa Boya #PrideEveryMonth

Alongside @SECTION27news & @EElawcentre we took govt to court & took to the streets to demand #SchoolMealsNow! Watch our joint actions here👇🏾 https://t.co/jIvWR5zjxp

Joint media advisory: VICTORY for Equal Education, Limpopo SGBs and over nine million learners in SA as court rules that govt school nutrition programme must immediately resume for all learners! https://t.co/WfL6ouMiYX
#SchoolMealsNow #9MillionMeals @EElawcentre @SECTION27news https://t.co/ieUvMdHNgW

Today, Acting Deputy Judge President of the North Gauteng High Court, Judge Sulet Potterill delivered judgment in the Equal Education and others v. the Department of Basic Education and others case, regarding the Schools Nutrition Programme (NSNP). #9MillionMeals #SchoolMealsNow

The court handed down both a declaratory and supervisory order, ordering the Department of Basic Education (DBE) to roll out the NSNP to all eligible children without delay – regardless of whether learners have returned to school #9MillionMeals #SchoolMealsNow

Represented by @EElawcentre & @SECTION27news, with counsel Geoff Budlender SC, @TembekaNgcukai1 SC & @Thabee_p . We celebrate this victory for over 9mil learners who depend on NSNP & the learners & caregivers who put their testimonies before court #9MillionMeals #SchoolMealsNow

In an NB piece of jurisprudence, the court granted a declaratory order, reiterating constitutional & statutory duty of @DBE_SA & the provincial edu departs to fulfil learners’ constitutional rights to basic nutrition & basic edu by delivering NSNP #9MillionMeals #SchoolMealsNow

The judgment also, in a supervisory interdict, orders Basic Education Minister Motshekga & Edu MECs of 8 provinces to file detailed plans for the resumption of the NSNP to all eligible learners within 10 days #SchoolMealsNow #9MillionMeals

Thereafter, Minister Motshekga & MECs will be required to file updates with court every 15 days to prove that plans to provide meals to learners are actually being implemented. #SchoolMealsNow #9MillionMeals

In her judgment, Judge Poterrill reflected: “Children are categorically vulnerable, poor hungry children are exceptionally vulnerable. The degree of the violation of the constitutional rights are thus egregious.” #SchoolMealsNow  #9MillionMeals

We welcome the judgment for its recognition that constitutional rights to basic nutrition & basic edu are inextricably linked - a victory not only for the 9mil learners but also millions of households whose food security has been gravely compromised #SchoolMealsNow #9MillionMeals

For learners to receive meals at school will ease the strain on caregivers – many of whom have lost their income and are struggling to put food on the table. #9MillionMeals #SchoolMealsNow #FamiliesNeedNSNP

We look forward to examining the plans put forward by @DBE_SA & provincial edu depts for the full resumption of the NSNP, as well as the progress reports, to ensure that the rights of learners to basic nutrition, basic edu and equality are upheld #SchoolMealsNow #9MillionMeals

Day By Day

The live-music business went from preparing for a summer with over 50 million advance tickets sold and a 30% year-over-year increase in shows scheduled to facing a nationwide directive prohibiting gatherings of 10 or more people.

Overnight, billions of dollars in ticket revenue and artist payments were frozen in accounts controlled by, respectively, Live Nation and AEG, and the four major talent agencies: WME, Creative Artists Agency (CAA), Paradigm and UTA.
Everyone else in the business — indie promoters, staging companies and food/merchandise vendors — continued to receive bills but not the money they were counting on to pay them.

With virtually all live events canceled or postponed through at least July, the industry as a whole — which, before the pandemic, had employed 50,000 salaried and contract employees and 200,000 part-time and seasonal workers — could be on track to lose $10 billion to $12 billion.

Every day after April 1 that Live Nation can’t put on concerts, it misses $30.3 million in revenue, based on 2019 second-quarter financial results. Already, the company’s stock price has dropped by half, wiping out $9 billion in market value

Live Nation is coming off its best year ever: Its 2019 revenue was up 7% to $11.5 billion, with operating income up 19% to $325 million. It also holds $2 billion in cash reserves, another $950 million in accounts receivable and owns Ticketmaster,

#GoodmorningAfrica Today’s interactive Doodle celebrates Zimbabwe’s national instrument, the mbira, as #Zimbabwe’s Culture Week begins. 

Originating in Southern Africa, the mbira has long played an integral role in the traditions and cultural identity of Zimbabwe’s Shona people. https://t.co/e9IVbY09Ja
It consists of a handheld hardwood soundboard (gwariva) affixed with a series of thin metal keys, which are plucked by the thumbs and forefinger. https://t.co/xvX21UN6Bt

A large hollow gourd (deze) provides amplification, and materials such as bottle caps or beads can be affixed to the soundboard to create the instrument’s signature buzzing sound.

Brendan Boyle, my father, died peacefully at home on Sunday evening. The tragedy of his death cannot be overstated, but my mother, brother and I have been touched to read all the kind words being written about him. It is comforting to know that we are not alone in our sadness.

He was a great man and an exceptional journalist, but he was also the most wonderful father anyone could hope to have. Some of my earliest memories are of projects we did together, like the model rocket whose parachute worked so well we never saw it again.

As a child, he always made me feel safe – even when climbing a mountain or sailing stormy seas. 

Over 38 years, his unconditional love, wise guidance and stellar example have shaped me into a man I am proud to be.

He taught me to be kind but honest, open minded but critical, polite but firm and compassionate but level-headed. 

I love him so much, and the world won’t be the same without him. 

  - Jordan Boyle (jordanboyle@gmail.com)

A short story about that Senegal team - whose openness was legendary. Journalists like me, @AliouGoloko & @DuncanCastles were welcomed in to areas usually off limits - as the team played cards, or drums, or messed around, whatever.

When they played a friendly in South Korea in late 01 I went along - as did @DuncanCastles - his previous photo reminded me of this story. Anyway I was just out of uni, trying to make it as a freelance and paid my way to Korea

After the game I went to the team’s hotel to do some interviews. I didn’t really know where I would stay but figured I’d find somewhere cheaper nearby. At some point the coach, the late great Bruno Metsu, asked where I was staying
When I said I wasn’t sure, he said he was in a double room, and offered me his spare bed...

It was - by any standards - a pretty unusual offer. Perhaps he took pity on me - or liked the fact I was interested in his team (several months before they beat France in the first game of the 2002 World Cup).
Anyway that Lions team was fabulously welcoming (and talented). You get a glimpse of that I hope in this piece I wrote after they beat France in 2002 https://t.co/2UZ6wqOZGy

🛏️ #SouthAfrica’s police minister Bheki Cele has claimed that 34,000 hospital beds are being occupied by alcohol-related cases. 

But is he right? https://t.co/OMBZnaDRbu

Experts don’t know where the minister’s figure came from. An unpublished study estimated there were 11,750 alcohol-related trauma admissions per week after the alcohol ban was lifted. https://t.co/OMBZnaDRbu
@Byron_McFadden We rated it 'unproven' as the study in question is still being peer-reviewed and hasn't yet been published.

Prof Andrew Nicol of the University of Cape Town, who the ministerial spokesperson said was the source of the figure, confirmed he had been involved in the study modelling the effect of the lockdown on trauma admissions. https://t.co/OMBZnaDRbu
But the study did not predict close to 34,000 extra or current alcohol-related admissions & experts had no idea how this figure was obtained. https://t.co/OMBZnaDRbu

That being said, an expert did confirm that alcohol does affect a hospital’s trauma case load: “There is the obvious increase in all mechanisms of injury at times when alcohol is bought and consumed in great volumes.”

🇳🇬 In his #DemocracyDay2020 speech Nigeria’s President @MBuhari spoke to the progress made under his administration, incl. economic growth, revenue from non-oil exports & the ease of doing business in the country. 

We checked 8 of his claims for accuracy. https://t.co/Y1Yy8DAeiQ

@MBuhari 📈 @MBuhari #DemocracyDay2020 claim: “We have witnessed 11 quarters of consecutive GDP growth since exiting recession.”

Verdict: Correct https://t.co/Y1Yy8DiCUg

@MBuhari 💰 @MBuhari #DemocracyDay2020 claim: “‘The GDP grew from 1.91% in 2018 to 2.27% in 2019 but declined to 1.87% in the first quarter of 2020 as a result of the decline in global economic activities due to the Covid-19 pandemic.”

Verdict: Misleading https://t.co/Y1Yy8DiCUg

@MBuhari An expert says while #COVID19 was a contributing factor, a drop in both oil prices & the demand for #Nigeria’s oil before the pandemic is a key reason. Added to this is a fall in regional trade after Nigeria shut its land borders in late 2019 in an effort to prevent smuggling.

@MBuhari 🗺️ @MBuhari #DemocracyDay2020 claim: “Every single economy in the world has suffered a decline.”

Verdict: Exaggerated https://t.co/Y1Yy8DiCUg

@MBuhari 💲 @MBuhari #DemocracyDay2020 claim: “The external reserves grew from $33.42 billion on 29 April 2020 to about $36 billion in May 2020.”

Verdict: Mostly correct https://t.co/Y1Yy8DiCUg

@MBuhari 💵 @MBuhari #DemocracyDay2020 claim: “[This amount in reserves] is enough to finance seven months of import commitments.”

Verdict: Unproven https://t.co/Y1Yy8DAeiQ

Did you know? Claims with no evidence to back them up are harder to check, but can't always be written off as wrong. 

To check them, look at credible data sources, verified experts and crowdsourced information.

#KeepTheFactsGoing https://t.co/MxaSNfNBwm

@MBuhari 🍫 @MBuhari #DemocracyDay2020 claim: “Our revenue from cocoa and sesame seed increased by $79.4 million and $153 million.”

Verdict: Unproven https://t.co/Y1Yy8DAeiQ

@MBuhari There has certainly been an increase in the value of the two exports in the past year, but the figures provided by the president do not tally with those published by the statistics agency. https://t.co/Y1Yy8DiCUg

If the claim was based on a survey, ask yourself: was the sample large enough? And was it comprehensive?

Verify  where and when the data was collected and how it was analysed. 

#KeepTheFactsGoing and visit https://t.co/6juqy5vVHk. https://t.co/ZUlmnubZ4E

@MBuhari 🗒️ @MBuhari #DemocracyDay2020 claim: “Nigeria has risen by 25 places on the World Bank’s ease of doing business ranking, from 146th to 131st.”

Verdict: Incorrect https://t.co/Y1Yy8DiCUg
@MBuhari While Nigeria’s 2020 ranking is a 15-spot jump on the previous year, it is the same ranking it had in 2013, when 185 countries were rated. https://t.co/Y1Yy8DAeiQ https://t.co/jIllHCIVCe

@MBuhari 🔝 @MBuhari #DemocracyDay2020 claim: “[Nigeria] is now rated as one of the top ten reforming countries.”

Verdict: Correct https://t.co/Y1Yy8DiCUg
@MBuhari But experts disagree as to the value of the ranking, with some arguing that reforms are largely on paper but not in practice. https://t.co/Y1Yy8DAeiQ

🍻 President @CyrilRamaphosa recently bemoaned #SouthAfrica’s position “as one of the countries in the world that has a high alcohol consumption level”.

But what % of #SouthAfricans drink alcohol? Where does the country rank internationally? 

We checked. https://t.co/bq0ZtrMGcm

@CyrilRamaphosa The latest @WHO data shows that, on average, #SouthAfricans over 15 consumed 9.3 litres of pure alcohol each in 2016. The figure was 16.2 litres for men & 2.7 litres for women. https://t.co/bq0Zts4h3U

@CyrilRamaphosa Based on these figures, #SouthAfrica ranked 50th out of 195 countries for total alcohol consumed per capita in 2016. 

Moldova took the top spot with a per capita consumption of 15.2 litres, followed closely by Lithuania (15 litres) & the Czech Republic (14.4 litres). https://t.co/aW0yQkmT1x

@CyrilRamaphosa #SouthAfrica’s average per capita consumption was 1.45 times higher than the global average, which was 6.4 litres per person in 2016. 

The average consumption in sub-Saharan #Africa was 6.3 litres per person. https://t.co/bq0Zts4h3U
Read this week's newsletter: #Nigeria's president fact-checked, SA's alcohol burden & murder of females. https://t.co/HilmM5t1wU

@CyrilRamaphosa #FYI: Almost 70% of South Africans over 15 abstained from drinking alcohol in 2016. The issue in South Africa is high levels of binge drinking among those *who do drink*, experts say (Read: https://t.co/D96SbrY2EM).

🚭 [ANALYSIS] Has #SouthAfrica’s tobacco ban made a million or so smokers quit the habit, as claimed by @SAQuitline & re-shared by @HealthZA? 

Given the public health implications of such a big shift, we took a closer look at how the number was estimated. https://t.co/sVKTYnG2Dc

@SAQuitline @HealthZA The survey, conducted in April and May 2020, was anonymously completed by more than 16,000 people, of which 12,204 answers were analysed. 

In this sample, 16% of respondents reported having quit smoking “successfully”. https://t.co/sVKTYnoreC
Read this week's newsletter for more on #Kenya's 2020 'crisis' budget & stats about #SouthAfrica's smokers and alcohol ranking https://t.co/lfuXSOShjD

@SAQuitline @HealthZA The survey report estimates that before the #tobacco ban, 6.5 million adults in #SA regularly smoked cigarettes. According to @SAQuitline, 16% of 6.5 million “is 1,040,000”. “Thus it is a safe estimate that 800,000 to 1 million smokers above 18 have stopped smoking.”

@SAQuitline @HealthZA But there are shortcomings. The questionnaire was “likely to be completed by more affluent and connected people” & one has to account for selection bias, meaning that those “particularly interested in the topic tend to be more willing to complete the survey than a random sample.

@SAQuitline @HealthZA Plus, the survey relied on self-reporting. It asked: “Have you successfully quit smoking over lockdown?” No definition of what “successfully” quitting meant was given. People are also likely to start smoking again after quitting. https://t.co/sVKTYnoreC

@SAQuitline @HealthZA While the survey used to support this claim likely overstates the number of people who quit smoking, an expert said there was “significance to the overarching point that the lockdown has made it easier for many people to quit smoking”.

@SAQuitline @HealthZA “Even if the numbers are overstated, it still means that making tobacco products less accessible is likely to reduce smoking rates,” he says, even as the survey called for an end to the ban due to a growth of the illicit market. https://t.co/sVKTYnG2Dc
